<div id="review_5178218" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/5178218" />
    <a title="Nidhi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/313365-nidhi"><img alt="Nidhi" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/5178218?book_show_action=true">Aug 27, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nidhi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nidhi" href="/user/show/313365-nidhi">Nidhi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone with an hour to kill</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer5178218" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9189348547118809628">He is a fairly pompous writer. I will start with that because it&apos;s important to know the tone from which you will be inflicted pages and pages of advice on how to be &quot;proper&quot; reader in today&apos;s society. This book is a series of essays written by Jonathan Franzen recently as well as revisited essays from his past. He laments the fall of the novelist, the over-importance put to privacy and the lack of care afforded to the the public, and deteriorating postal systems (this essay, I must be honest, I</span>
  <span id="freeText9189348547118809628" style="display:none">He is a fairly pompous writer. I will start with that because it's important to know the tone from which you will be inflicted pages and pages of advice on how to be "proper" reader in today's society. This book is a series of essays written by Jonathan Franzen recently as well as revisited essays from his past. He laments the fall of the novelist, the over-importance put to privacy and the lack of care afforded to the the public, and deteriorating postal systems (this essay, I must be honest, I did not finish because it just droned on and on and I simply moved on). He offers substantive view points on modern civilization and the things that waste away our days and take time away from more noble forms leisure - he also submits that there may not be anything to be done about the fall of society. Each essay does have some great ideas which I may from time to time reread, and he is a very good writer in the sense that he states his point clearly and with purpose. <br /><br />I will end with saying that it's a decent book of semi-interesting essays. I wouldn't buy it again if I went back in time but I might borrow it.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9189348547118809628" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


