<div id="review_2277212106" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2277212106" />
    <a title="Matt Schiavenza" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7937368-matt-schiavenza"><img alt="Matt Schiavenza" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483150236p2/7937368.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2277212106?book_show_action=true">Feb 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt Schiavenza" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt Schiavenza" href="/user/show/7937368-matt-schiavenza">Matt Schiavenza</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2277212106" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1754741389324321973">I remember Franzen exploding onto the scene due to the controversy over Oprah&apos;s book club — his novel, The Corrections, had been chosen for inclusion but Franzen refused to go on the show in protest of Oprah&apos;s effect on book sales. I found this to be an overly precious position and avoided Franzen as a result. <br/><br/>But some of my friends raved about him and I thought I&apos;d take a shot on a book of essays. Like all collections of the sort, this one is of variable quality. A story about his father&apos;s affl</span>
  <span id="freeText1754741389324321973" style="display:none">I remember Franzen exploding onto the scene due to the controversy over Oprah's book club — his novel, The Corrections, had been chosen for inclusion but Franzen refused to go on the show in protest of Oprah's effect on book sales. I found this to be an overly precious position and avoided Franzen as a result. <br /><br />But some of my friends raved about him and I thought I'd take a shot on a book of essays. Like all collections of the sort, this one is of variable quality. A story about his father's affliction with Alzheimer's is extraordinarily beautiful and powerful; and a reported piece on the travails of a post office in Chicago is an excellent piece of journalism.<br /><br />Some of the other stories are more precious than illuminating, while some meander so much that I found it difficult to read all the way through. But it's hard to escape the conclusion that Franzen is an immensely skilled writer and original thinker who, in retrospect, was probably right about the Oprah dust-up anyway.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1754741389324321973" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


